Event Driven Production Game¶

The Market¶

  • The state of the market is product demand of the form $P = a-\beta_s Q$, where $\beta_s$ is determined by the state of the market.
  • The market spontaneously changes state at a rate of $\lambda_m$
  • The market sends messages to the player 1 and 2 at a rate of $\mu_1$ and $\mu_2$, respectively.

Players¶

  • 2 human controlled SFTs that represent firms
  • The players only have one state
  • The player's choose production quantities upon receiving a message from the market by sending messages to the market. Products go to market at a rate of $\nu_1$ and $\nu_2$.
  • In short, the player's can receive messages from the market at different times and their messages (which are quantities) can reach the market at different times.

Equilibrium¶

  • The price is determined by the state of the market and the most recent message from both players.

  • Rewards are accumulated as profit, computed as $P\times Q-CQ$, per unit time. $C$ is an exogenously specified per-unit cost.

Other Points¶

  • The game is infinite horizon
  • Rewards are discounted

    ############################# ACTION NEEDS TO BE REDEFINED TO BE A STRATEGY! ###
    strategy::Dict{(Message, Any), (Message, Any)} # CHANGE THIS TO ANY ANY SINCE MESSAGES MIGHT BE AN ARRAY
    
    
    statespace::Array{Any, 1} # The state space
    currentstate::Any
    quantity_since_last_event::Float64
    name::ASCIIString
    trembling::Bool
    trembleprob::Float64
    ## Technically, quantitysincelastevent is a deterministic
    ## element of the state space given the messages.  Here it is used
    ## for accounting purposes.  Last event is last event in the game.
end


# In general, the set of available actions should depend on the state/message received.  However, in
# this game, the player is only going to change his state and send messages and this will not depend
# on his current state or the message he receives.  Therefore, the elements of 'action' are probably going
# to be tuples of the form (Message, State Transition).  Therefore, we can define actions as the cross product of
# messages and states;

# But it should be as simple as changing the MCTSvalues dict to be the strategy
# In other words, if the strategy is a dictionary keyed by messages and states and it's values are
# tuples of actions and state changed

function receive_message_and_react(sft::Player, message::Message)
    #     This function will have a player receive a message and then emit
    #     a message and possibly change its state.  If the current state of the players
    #     and the received message has not yet occured for the player, the player will 
    #     pick a message uniformly random.  If the player has received the message in 
    #     his current state, he will do UCT.  
        
    #     Note, this function does NOT update the MCTS nodes, it only picks the player's
    #     action.

    #     Output is a message.  The Player object may also change its currentstate method
    if ~ sft.trembling
        action = sft.strategy[message, sft.currentstate]
        sft.currentstate = action[2]
    else
        if rand() < sft.trembleprob
            action = (sample(sft.messages), sample(sft.statespace))
            sft.currentstate = action[2]
        else
            action = sft.strategy[message, sft.currentstate]
            sft.currentstate = action[2]
        end
    end
    return action
end;

SFTNet-Methods¶

In [40]:
function resetnet(net::SFTNet)
    net.market.state = net.market.statespace[1]
    net.messagesintransit = Message[]
    for p in net.players
        net.market.quantitiesinmarket[p.name] = 0
        p.quantity_since_last_event = 0
    end
end;

Functions Called During Simulation¶

In [41]:
function handle_event(event::Any, net::SFTNet)
    if typeof(event) == Spont
        return receive_message_and_react(net.market, event)
    elseif event.receiver=="Market"
        return receive_message_and_react(net.market, event)
    else
        return receive_message_and_react(net.sftdict[event.receiver], event)
    end
end;
In [42]:
function get_possible_events(net::SFTNet)
    return [net.messagesintransit, net.market.spont[net.market.state]]
end;
In [43]:
function get_time_increment(possible_events::Array)
    sumrate = sum([e.rate for e in possible_events])
    return rand(Exponential(1/sumrate))
end;
In [44]:
function generate_random_strategy(messages_to_send::Array{Message, 1}, messages_to_receive::Array{Message, 1}, 
    statespace)
    strategy = Dict{(Message, Any), (Message, Any)}()
    for instate in statespace
        for m_in in messages_to_receive
            messageout = sample(messages_to_send)
            newstate = sample(statespace)
            strategy[(m_in, instate)] = (messageout, newstate)
        end
    end
    return strategy
end;

## SPECIAL NOTE!!! FOR THE MARKET, WE DEFINE THE RATE OF EVENT FOR EACH
## POSSIBLE SPONTANEOUS EVENT INSTEAD OF SPECIFYING A RATE OF SPONTANEOUS EVENTS
## AND A PI^SP.  IT TURNS OUT TO BE A TAD EASIER COMPUTATIONALLY.

mkt_to_p1 = 1.
mkt_to_p2 = 1.
market_state_space = [(50, 1), (50, 2),(50, 3)]
p1quantities = [range(1,19)]
p2quantities = [range(1,19)]
p1tomarket = 1.
p2tomarket = 1.
p1statespace = ASCIIString["Memory1"]
p2statespace = ASCIIString["Memory1"]
market_change_rate = .25
discount=.25
p1c = 1.
p2c = 1.

#END PARAMETERS#


function build_net_for_experiment(mkt_to_p1::Float64, mkt_to_p2::Float64, market_state_space, p1quantities,
    p2quantities, p1tomarket::Float64, p2tomarket::Float64, p1statespace, p2statespace, market_change_rate::Float64, 
    discount::Float64, p1c, p2c, trembling=false, trembleprob=0.0)
    # DEFINE AND COLLECT ALL POSSIBLE MESSAGES IN THE GAME#
    p1messages = Message[]
    p2messages = Message[]
    marketmessages = Message[]
    # First let's generate market messages to each player
    for s in market_state_space
        push!(marketmessages, Message("Market", "Player 1", s, mkt_to_p1))
        push!(marketmessages, Message("Market", "Player 2", s, mkt_to_p2))
    end

    for q in p1quantities
        push!(p1messages, Message("Player 1", "Market", q, p1tomarket))
    end

    for q in p2quantities
        push!(p2messages, Message("Player 2", "Market", q, p2tomarket))
    end    
    # Now generate message from players to market
    # END DEFINE ALL MESSAGES#

    ## DEFINE AND COLLECT ALL SPONTANEOUS EVENTS FOR THE MARKET
    market_spon_dict = Dict()
    ## The market is a random walk on the index of the statespace
    ## Therefore, when defining the statespace of the market, it makes sense to
    ## "order" the states.
    for ix in 1:length(market_state_space)
        if ix ==1
            market_spon_dict[market_state_space[ix]] = Spont[]
            s_event = Spont("Market", market_change_rate, market_state_space[2], marketmessages[3:4])
            push!(market_spon_dict[market_state_space[ix]], s_event)

        elseif ix == length(market_state_space)
            market_spon_dict[market_state_space[ix]] = Spont[]
            s_event = Spont("Market", market_change_rate, market_state_space[(length(market_state_space) -1)],
                [marketmessages[(length(marketmessages) - 3) : (length(marketmessages) - 2)]])
            push!(market_spon_dict[market_state_space[ix]], s_event)
        else
            start_ix = 2*ix +1
            end_ix = 2*ix+2
            market_spon_dict[market_state_space[ix]] = Spont[]
            s_event = Spont("Market", market_change_rate/2., market_state_space[(ix+1)],
                [marketmessages[start_ix : end_ix]])
            push!(market_spon_dict[market_state_space[ix]], s_event)
            start_ix = 2*ix-3
            end_ix = 2*ix-2
            s_event = Spont("Market", market_change_rate/2., market_state_space[(ix+-1)],
                [marketmessages[start_ix : end_ix]])
            push!(market_spon_dict[market_state_space[ix]], s_event)
        end
    end
    ## END MARKET SPONTANEOUS EVENTS

    # This is annoying because Julia does not have conditional list comprehension
    messages_to_p1 = Message[]
    messages_to_p2 = Message[]
    for m in marketmessages
        if m.receiver=="Player 1"
            push!(messages_to_p1, m)
        else
            push!(messages_to_p2, m)
        end
    end
    p1_strategy = generate_random_strategy(p1messages, messages_to_p1, p1statespace)
    p2_strategy = generate_random_strategy(p2messages, messages_to_p2, p2statespace)
    qinmarket = ["Player 1"=>0, "Player 2"=>0]
    #CREATE SFTs#
    p1 = Player(discount, p1messages, p1c, p1_strategy, p1statespace, "Player 1", trembling, trembleprob);
    p2 = Player(discount, p2messages, p2c, p2_strategy, p2statespace, "Player 2", trembling, trembleprob);
    market = Market(market_change_rate, marketmessages, qinmarket, market_state_space, (50,1), "Market", market_spon_dict)
    #END CREATE SFTs#
    sft_dict = {"Player 1"=> p1, "Player 2"=>p2, "Market"=>market}

    # CREATE AND INTIALIZE THE SFTNET#
    net = SFTNet([p1, p2], market, Message[], sft_dict)
    # END CREATE AND INITIALIZE THE SFTNET#;
    return net
end

A note on profits¶

We assume that profits are accumulated continuously. Therefore, total utility is given by \begin{equation} \int_0^\infty e^{-\beta t}\pi(t)dt. \end{equation}

However, profits only change when either the market changes state (demand shock) or a new product quantity is received by the market.
Therefore, if we let $\tau_1, \tau_2...$ denote the times that the profit stream changes. Total utility is computed as

\begin{equation} \sum_{i=1}^{\infty}\int_{\tau_i}^{\tau_{i+1}} e^{-\beta t}\pi(t)dt. \end{equation}

where $\pi(t)$ is constant in any interval $(\tau_i, \tau_{i+1})$. This implies that for any interval, the contribution to total utility is given by

\begin{equation} \frac{e^{-\tau_i \beta} - e^{-\tau_{i+1} \beta}}{\beta}\pi \end{equation}
In [21]:
function get_profits(net::SFTNet, tau1::Float64, tau2::Float64)
    price = get_price(net.market)
    p1_profit = price * net.market.quantitiesinmarket["Player 1"] - 
        net.sftdict["Player 1"].cost * net.market.quantitiesinmarket["Player 1"]
    p2_profit = price * net.market.quantitiesinmarket["Player 2"] - 
        net.sftdict["Player 2"].cost * net.market.quantitiesinmarket["Player 2"]
    p1_discounted_profit = ( (e^(-tau1 * net.sftdict["Player 1"].discount) - e^(-tau2 * net.sftdict["Player 1"].discount)) * 
            p1_profit) /net.sftdict["Player 1"].discount
    p2_discounted_profit = ( (e^(-tau1 * net.sftdict["Player 2"].discount) - e^(-tau2 * net.sftdict["Player 2"].discount)) * 
            p2_profit) /net.sftdict["Player 2"].discount
    return [p1_discounted_profit, p2_discounted_profit]
end;
In [22]:
# Use some of this!
function simulate(net::SFTNet, t_end::Int64)
    t = 0.
    total_profits = [0,0]
    possible_events = get_possible_events(net)
    while t < t_end
        probs = WeightVec(Float64[e.rate for e in possible_events])
        event = sample(possible_events, probs)
        # An event is either a spontaneous transm/transi or a message received
        if (typeof(event)==Message)
            ix = findfirst(net.messagesintransit, event)
            splice!(net.messagesintransit, ix) # Removes the messge from the network
            # If the event is the player receiving a message
            if event.sender == "Market"
                player = net.sftdict[event.receiver]
                # "player" is now the Player type        
                action = handle_event(event, net)
                new_messages = action[1]
                net.messagesintransit = [net.messagesintransit, new_messages]
            else
                # If the event is the market receiving a message
                handle_event(event, net) # The market changes quantities in market
            end
        else
            new_messages = handle_event(event, net)
            net.messagesintransit = [net.messagesintransit, new_messages]
        end
        possible_events = get_possible_events(net)
        timeincrement = get_time_increment(possible_events)
        immediate_profits = get_profits(net, t, t+timeincrement)
        t += timeincrement
        total_profits += immediate_profits
    end
    return total_profits
end;

In [24]:
function compute_expected_utility(net::SFTNet, t_max::Int64, nruns::Int64)
    eu = [0,0]
    for s in 1:nruns
        eu += simulate(net, t_max)
    end
    return eu/nruns
end;

Initial Parameters¶

  • Intercept of demand is 50 but the slope $\in [1,2,3,4,5]$.
  • All messages traverse edges at a rate of 1
  • The market changes it's state at a rate of .25
  • The players submit any quantity in $[1,2,3...20]$
  • Discount rate is .25
  • Per unit cost is 1

Pre-PGT experiments¶

Although the game continues to infinity, because of a positive discount rate, the expected utilities should converge. Let's take a look and see what expected utility looks like for a given joint profile and different lengths of simulation. In this example we simulate the network 5000 times to estimate expected utility.

Again, this has nothing to do with PGT. Since the game is of infinite horizon, these simulations are meant to determine how many time steps is "enough" so that the expected utility is "close" to the expected utility if the game were to run until infinity.

In [25]:
net = build_net_for_experiment(mkt_to_p1, mkt_to_p2, market_state_space, p1quantities, p2quantities,
p1tomarket, p2tomarket, p1statespace, p2statespace, market_change_rate, discount, p1c, p2c);
eus = Array[]
for i in 1:50
    push!(eus, compute_expected_utility(net, i, 5000))
end

It looks like the expected utility becomes stationary around 20 time steps but there is still too much variance in the expected utility calculation, indicating we need to raise the number of samples. In other words, to estimate the expected utility when the simulation runs for $20$ timesteps, it is necessary to sample the stochastic process many times (since each run of the network does not yield the same reward for each player). However, if the number of simulations for a given length of simulation is not "high enough" there will still be variance in the expected utility.

Let's see how the expected utility behaves as we raise the number of times we simulate the network. This holds the length of simulation constant at 20.

In [27]:

end

So in this case, it looks like if we want a relative error less than one percent, we need to simulate the stochastic process 50000 times to get an estimate of expected utility with less than a 1% relative error.

Based on the profiling estimate, it takes 42 seconds to estimate expected utiliy to within 1% relative error. So, if we sample 30 alternative profiles for each player when computing intelligence, it will take 42 minutes to compute the intelligence of just one strategy profile.

In this case, the market has 5 states and the players have twenty actions. That means each player has 3.2 million profiles for a total of $3.2$M$^2$ or $10.24 \times 10^{12}$ joint profiles. If we wanted to compute the intelligence for one one-millionth ($10^{-6}$) of the total number of joint profiles, it would take us approximately $300000$ days.

So how do we solve this problem? Right now we just shrink the game.

That means that each player has $10^3$ possible strategies and a total of $1$M joint profiles. Let's do some more profiling like above.

Distributions of Utility¶

To know what we are looking at, let's first see what the distribution of the player's expected utility looks like when we give equal weight to all (sampled) profiles. In [28]:
function uniformhistogram(net::SFTNet, n_profiles=1)
    messages_to_p1 = Message[]
    messages_to_p2 = Message[]
    for m in net.market.messages
        if m.receiver=="Player 1"
            push!(messages_to_p1, m)
        else
            push!(messages_to_p2, m)
        end
    end
    eus = Any[]
    for run in 1:n_profiles
        p1_strategy = generate_random_strategy(net.sftdict["Player 1"].messages, messages_to_p1, 
            net.sftdict["Player 1"].statespace)
        p2_strategy = generate_random_strategy(net.sftdict["Player 2"].messages, messages_to_p2, 
            net.sftdict["Player 2"].statespace)
        net.sftdict["Player 1"].strategy = p1_strategy
        net.sftdict["Player 2"].strategy = p2_strategy
        push!(eus, compute_expected_utility(net, 20, 40000))
    end
    return eus
end;

PGT¶


















In this section, we finally do PGT and look at the distribution of expected utilities where the probability of a profile is determined by intelligence.  Here we seek to estimate the intelligence of 1.4% (14,000) of the joint profiles.













In [3]:



    


function PGT(paramdict::Any)
    mkt_to_p1 = paramdict["mkt_to_p1"]
    mkt_to_p2 = paramdict["mkt_to_p2"]
    market_state_space = paramdict["market_state_space"]
    p1quantities = paramdict["p1quantities"]
    p2quantities = paramdict["p2quantities"]
    p1tomarket = paramdict["p1tomarket"]
    p2tomarket = paramdict["p2tomarket"]
    p1statespace = paramdict["p1statespace"]
    p2statespace = paramdict["p2statespace"]
    market_change_rate = paramdict["market_change_rate"]
    discount= paramdict["discount"]
    p1c = paramdict["p1c"]
    p2c = paramdict["p2c"]
    numprofiles = paramdict["numprofiles"]
    numalt = paramdict["numalt"]
    eu_nsims = paramdict["eunumsims"]
    eu_tmax = paramdict["eu_tmax"]
    tremble = paramdict["trembling"]
    tremble_prob = paramdict["tremble_prob"]
    
    net = build_net_for_experiment(mkt_to_p1, mkt_to_p2, market_state_space, p1quantities, p2quantities,
                                    p1tomarket, p2tomarket, p1statespace, p2statespace, market_change_rate, 
                                    discount, p1c, p2c, tremble, tremble_prob)
    messages_to_p1 = Message[]
    messages_to_p2 = Message[]
    for m in net.market.messages
        if m.receiver=="Player 1"
            push!(messages_to_p1, m)
        else
            push!(messages_to_p2, m)
        end
    end
    # Get these at the beginning so we don't have to keep searching player types
    p1possible = net.sftdict["Player 1"].messages
    p2possible = net.sftdict["Player 2"].messages
    p1statespace = net.sftdict["Player 1"].statespace 
    p2statespace = net.sftdict["Player 2"].statespace
    joint_strats_eu = Dict{(Dict, Dict), Array{Float64}}() #Keeps track of 
    p1_utilities = Float64[]
    p2_utilities = Float64[]
    intels = Float64[]
    for jps in 1:numprofiles
        print(jps)
        p1_strategy = generate_random_strategy(p1possible, messages_to_p1, 
            p1statespace)
        p2_strategy = generate_random_strategy(p2possible, messages_to_p2, 
            p2statespace)
        net.sftdict["Player 1"].strategy = p1_strategy
        net.sftdict["Player 2"].strategy = p2_strategy
        eu_outer = compute_expected_utility(net, eu_tmax, eu_nsims)
        push!(p1_utilities, eu_outer[1])
        push!(p2_utilities, eu_outer[2])
        joint_strats_eu[p1_strategy, p2_strategy] = eu_outer
        num_no_betterp1 = 0
        num_no_betterp2 = 0
        for a in 1:numalt
            p1altstrat = generate_random_strategy(p1possible, messages_to_p1, 
                p1statespace)
            net.sftdict["Player 1"].strategy = p1altstrat
            if haskey(joint_strats_eu, (p1altstrat, p2_strategy))
                eu_inner = joint_strats_eu[(p1altstrat, p2_strategy)]
            else
                eu_inner = compute_expected_utility(net, eu_tmax, eu_nsims)
                joint_strats_eu[p1altstrat, p2_strategy] = eu_inner
            end
            if eu_inner[1] < eu_outer[1]
                num_no_betterp1 += 1
            end
        end
        net.sftdict["Player 1"].strategy = p1_strategy
        for a in 1:numalt
            p2altstrat = generate_random_strategy(p2possible, messages_to_p2, 
                p2statespace)
            net.sftdict["Player 2"].strategy = p2altstrat
            if haskey(joint_strats_eu, (p1_strategy, p2altstrat))
                eu_inner = joint_strats_eu[(p1_strategy, p2altstrat)]
            else
                eu_inner = compute_expected_utility(net, eu_tmax, eu_nsims)
                joint_strats_eu[p1_strategy, p2altstrat] = eu_inner
            end
            if eu_inner[2] < eu_outer[2]
                num_no_betterp2 += 1
            end
        end
        intel = (num_no_betterp1/numalt) * (num_no_betterp2/numalt)
        push!(intels, intel)
    end
    return intels, p1_utilities, p2_utilities
end

PGT (generic function with 1 method)



















In [ ]:



    


pmap(PGT, [params, params, params, params, params, params, params, params])























Unfortunately, at about 15 hours running this simulation on all 8 cores of my machine, my computer crashed.  The reason this takes so long is because to get an "accurate" estimate of expected utility, we need to simulate the SFTNet many (10000 times).  Even by recording the expected utility for all profiles and not-recomputing expected utility for previously computed profiles, the time it takes to do PGT is on the order of hours/days. However, since we only care about the ordering of expected utilities for the joint profile we are "wasting" samples when the expected utilities are far apart.  To assuage this, I propose a confidence interval based intelligence.  In summary it is as follows:


1) Sample a joint strategy profile and compute the expected utility "almost exactly" (i.e. with a large number of runs).


2) For each alternative joint strategy profile, begin sampling the stochastic process to compute the expected utility.


3) (Suppose we are computing the intelligence for player 1's profile).  After each sample of the network, compute the confidence interval of player 1's expected utility under his alternative strategy at a pre-specified significance level.


4) If the expected utility of player 1's "outerloop" strategy is outside of the confidence interval of player 1's expected utility under the alternative strategy, classify the alternative strategy as either better or worse than the outerloop strategy according to whether the outerloop strategy is above or below the confidence interval.


5) Set a predefined maximum number of simulations in case the outerloop expected utility is never outside of the confidence interval.













In [72]:



    


function is_worse(net::SFTNet, t_max::Int64, nruns::Int64, baseeu::Float64, player::Int64,
    confintmin=50, z=2.576)
    ## The player is the index to compare in the simulate output.
    runningeu = 0
    sse = 0
    s = 1
    running_sum_squares= 0
    while s < nruns
        utility = simulate(net, t_max)[player]
        e = utility - runningeu
        runningeu += e/s
        sse += e* (utility - runningeu)
        variance = sse/s
        s += 1
        if s >confintmin
            # confintmin large enough so that we can approximate the mean by a normal distribution, not t.
            conf_l = runningeu - z*(variance/s)^.5
            conf_u = runningeu + z*(variance/s)^.5
            if (baseeu < conf_l) | (baseeu>conf_u)
                s = nruns #Exit Loop
            end
        end
    end
    return runningeu
end;

function CI_PGT(paramdict::Any)
    mkt_to_p1 = paramdict["mkt_to_p1"]
    mkt_to_p2 = paramdict["mkt_to_p2"]
    market_state_space = paramdict["market_state_space"]
    p1quantities = paramdict["p1quantities"]
    p2quantities = paramdict["p2quantities"]
    p1tomarket = paramdict["p1tomarket"]
    p2tomarket = paramdict["p2tomarket"]
    p1statespace = paramdict["p1statespace"]
    p2statespace = paramdict["p2statespace"]
    market_change_rate = paramdict["market_change_rate"]
    discount= paramdict["discount"]
    p1c = paramdict["p1c"]
    p2c = paramdict["p2c"]
    numprofiles = paramdict["numprofiles"]
    numalt = paramdict["numalt"]
    eu_nsims = paramdict["eunumsims"]
    eu_tmax = paramdict["eu_tmax"]
    tremble = paramdict["trembling"]
    tremble_prob = paramdict["tremble_prob"]
    
    net = build_net_for_experiment(mkt_to_p1, mkt_to_p2, market_state_space, p1quantities, p2quantities,
                                    p1tomarket, p2tomarket, p1statespace, p2statespace, market_change_rate, 
                                        discount, p1c, p2c, tremble, tremble_prob)
    messages_to_p1 = Message[]
    messages_to_p2 = Message[]
    for m in net.market.messages
        if m.receiver=="Player 1"
            push!(messages_to_p1, m)
        else
            push!(messages_to_p2, m)
        end
    end
    # Get these at the beginning so we don't have to keep searching player types
    p1possible = net.sftdict["Player 1"].messages
    p2possible = net.sftdict["Player 2"].messages
    p1statespace = net.sftdict["Player 1"].statespace 
    p2statespace = net.sftdict["Player 2"].statespace
    sampled_strats = Any[]
    p1_utilities = Float64[]
    p2_utilities = Float64[]
    intels = Float64[]
    for jps in 1:numprofiles
        p1_strategy = generate_random_strategy(p1possible, messages_to_p1, 
            p1statespace)
        p2_strategy = generate_random_strategy(p2possible, messages_to_p2, 
            p2statespace)
        ## Need to compute twice, on for player 1 trembing and one for player 1
        push!(sampled_strats, (p1_strategy, p2_strategy))
        net.sftdict["Player 1"].strategy = p1_strategy
        net.sftdict["Player 2"].strategy = p2_strategy
        #Player 1
        net.sftdict["Player 1"].trembling=false
        net.sftdict["Player 2"].trembling=true
        eu_outer = compute_expected_utility(net, eu_tmax, eu_nsims)
        push!(p1_utilities, eu_outer[1])
        #Player 2
        net.sftdict["Player 1"].trembling=true
        net.sftdict["Player 2"].trembling=false
        eu_outer = compute_expected_utility(net, eu_tmax, eu_nsims)
        push!(p2_utilities, eu_outer[2])
        
        #joint_strats_eu[p1_strategy, p2_strategy] = eu_outer
        num_no_betterp1 = 0
        num_no_betterp2 = 0
        for a in 1:numalt
            net.sftdict["Player 1"].trembling=false
            net.sftdict["Player 2"].trembling=true
            p1altstrat = generate_random_strategy(p1possible, messages_to_p1, 
                p1statespace)
            net.sftdict["Player 1"].strategy = p1altstrat
            eu_inner = is_worse(net, eu_tmax, eu_nsims, eu_outer[1], 1)
            if eu_inner < eu_outer[1]
                num_no_betterp1 += 1
            end
        end
        net.sftdict["Player 1"].strategy = p1_strategy
        for a in 1:numalt
            net.sftdict["Player 1"].trembling=true
            net.sftdict["Player 2"].trembling=false
            p2altstrat = generate_random_strategy(p2possible, messages_to_p2, 
                p2statespace)
            net.sftdict["Player 2"].strategy = p2altstrat
            eu_inner = is_worse(net, eu_tmax, eu_nsims, eu_outer[2], 2)
            if eu_inner < eu_outer[2]
                num_no_betterp2 += 1
            end
        end
        intel = (num_no_betterp1/numalt) * (num_no_betterp2/numalt)
        push!(intels, intel)
    end
    return intels, p1_utilities, p2_utilities, sampled_strats
end;

















In [5]:



    


function split_pgt_parallel(pgtres)
    intels = Float64[]
    p1util = Float64[]
    p2util = Float64[]
    strats = Any[]
    for core in pgtres
        for simnum in 1:length(core[1])
            if ~ (core[4][simnum] in strats)
                push!(strats, core[4][simnum])
                push!(intels, core[1][simnum])
                push!(p1util, core[2][simnum])
                push!(p2util, core[3][simnum])
            end
        end
    end
    return strats, intels, p1util, p2util
end

using DataStructures
function plot_intelligence_cdf(intels::Array, utility::Array)
    normedprobs = intels/sum(intels)
    d=Dict{Float64, Float64}()
    # DefaultDict is not working right now.  I will just do
    # this the poor man's way
    for util_ix in 1:length(utility)
        d[utility[util_ix]] = 0
    end
    for util_ix in 1:length(utility)
        d[utility[util_ix]] += normedprobs[util_ix]
    end
    u2 = Float64[]
    p2 = Float64[]
    for (key, val) in d
        push!(u2, key)
        push!(p2, val)
    end
    std_util = sort(u2)
    std_util_ix = sortperm(u2)
    std_prob = [p2[ix] for ix in std_util_ix]
    return std_util, cumsum(std_prob)
end

One possible solution to this is some of the "tremling hand" PGT calculations we used before.



















Though the trembling hand PGT approach does have its limitations, let's see what happens when we allow the players to tremble.


In this case, a tremble is not a complete strategy tremble but a tremble at random action times.  More specifically, when computing the intellgience of a strategy profile and computing the expected utility for player 1, player 2 plays an action according to his strategy with probability $p$.  Then, with probability $(1-p)$ he selects (uniformly) one of his other actions.

Scrap¶


















    

  • First we need to fix the player object
    

      

    • We want the player type to set a current strategy and have a container for all possible strategies
      • 

    

    • 

  • We need a function that simulates the network up to a prespecified number of time steps where player strategies are given.
    

    • 

  • We need a way to sample player strategies
    

      

    • Strategies are mapings from (input, state) to (output, state).
      • 

    • To get a full set of strategies, we need to know all possible messages a player can receive.
      • 

    • Need a function that takes as an input all SFTs in a game and outputs the pure strategy space for all players.
      • 

    

    • 

  • We need a way to compute expected utility for given strategies
    

      

    • This just requires simulating a bunch of times and averaging the output
      • 

    • Produce a graph that shows the convergence of expected utility vs the number of simulation
      • 

    • Produce a graph the shows the convergence of expected utility for a given number of time steps
      • 

    

    • 

  • Then we need a PGT algorithm
